maml:description.maml:para: Adds an alias to a QuickModuleCLI nested module.
Adds an alias to a QuickModuleCLI nested module that can later be auto-loaded based on your $PSModuleAutoLoadingPreference.

maml:Description.maml:para: Specifies the name of the NestedModule in which this function belongs.
Specifies the name of the new alias.
Specifies the name of the function to which this alias maps.
Specifies the name of the function to which this alias maps.
Specifies the name of the new alias.
Specifies the name of the NestedModule in which this function belongs.

dev:type.maml:name: None. You cannot pipe objects to Add-ModuleAlias.
None. Add-ModuleAlias creates a new alias that you can later use.

maml:alert.maml:para: Once created, every time you open a new Powershell window the alias will be exported for you to use. Once you attempt to use an alias for the first time in a powershell session it will auto-import the rest of the module for you.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Add-ModuleAlias -NestedModule Default -AliasName echo -AliasMappedFunction 'Write-Output'

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 2 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Add-ModuleAlias Default echo Write-Output

maml:description.maml:para: Adds a function to a QuickModuleCLI nested module.
Adds a function to a QuickModuleCLI nested module that can later be auto-loaded based on your $PSModuleAutoLoadingPreference.

maml:Description.maml:para: Specifies the name of the NestedModule in which this function belongs.
Specifies the name of the new function
Specifies the content that should go in the function. Line breaks will automatically be added after semi semicolons.
Specifies the name of the new function
Specifies the content that should go in the function. Line breaks will automatically be added after semi semicolons.
Specifies the name of the NestedModule in which this function belongs.

dev:type.maml:name: None. You cannot pipe objects to Add-ModuleFunction.
None. Add-ModuleFunction creates a new function that you can later use.

maml:alert.maml:para: Once created, every time you open a new Powershell window the function will be exported for you to use. Once you attempt to use a function for the first time in a powershell session it will auto-import the rest of the module for you.

If you use this function with the $functionText parameter, then your function will be automatically formatted with line breaks, wherever you had included semi-colons (;). Additionally, if you do not include the $functionText parameter, then this function will open your Powershell ISE for you to modify the function there.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Add-ModuleFunction -NestedModule Default -functionName Write-Echo -functionText 'Write-Output (Read-Host "Are you my echo?")'

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 2 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Add-ModuleFunction Default Write-Echo 'Please enter the Function: Write-Output (Read-Host "Are you my echo?")'

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 3 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Add-ModuleFunction Default Write-Echo

dev:remarks.maml:para: [PS ISE opens...] Press any key when you are finished editing...

maml:description.maml:para: Adds a system or user variable.
This function is a wrapper around the [Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable function. It first checks to see if the environment variable exists, then asks if you wish to overwrite it.

dev:type.maml:name: None. You cannot pipe objects to Set-Env
None. Set-Env creates environment configuration that you can later use.

maml:alert.maml:para: [EnvironmentVariableTarget] can be interpreted from the strings "User" or "Machine"

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Set-Env

dev:remarks.maml:para: Please enter Environment Variable Name: Desktop Please enter Environment Variable Value: C:\Users\User\Path-To-Desktop PS C:\> ... PS C:\>Set-Location $env:Desktop PS C:\Users\User\Path-To-Desktop>

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 2 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Set-Env -variable Desktop -value C:\Users\User\Path-To-Desktop

dev:remarks.maml:para: PS C:\> ... PS C:\>Set-Location $env:Desktop PS C:\Users\User\Path-To-Desktop>

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 3 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Set-Env -variable Desktop -value C:\Users\User\Path-To-Desktop

dev:remarks.maml:para: A value already exists for the User variable 'Desktop' Would you like to overwrite? [Y] Yes [N] No [?] Help (default is "N"):Y PS C:\> ... PS C:\>Set-Location $env:Desktop PS C:\Users\User\Path-To-Desktop>

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- EXAMPLE 4 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: Set-Env -variable MyApplication -value "C:\Program Files\Path-To-My-Application" -environmentVariableTarget "Machine"

dev:remarks.maml:para: PS C:\> ... PS C:\>Set-Location $env:MyApplication PS C:\Program Files\Path-To-My-Application>
